  protein: 37 g
  fiber: 5 g
  sodium: 1320 mg
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/cheddar-stuffed-meatloaves-6595d035050f2b642e9a301b
cuisine: North America
author: HelloFresh
servings: 2
course: main course
time required: 35 minutes
---

Adjust rack to top position (top and middle positions for 4 servings)
and preheat #oven{} to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch-thick wedges.
Trim, peel, and cut @carrots{9%ounce} on a diagonal into ¼-inch-thick pieces.
Halve, peel, and thinly slice @shallot{1}.

Trim and discard woody bottom ends from @asparagus{6%ounce}.

> Save carrots for another use.

Toss potatoes on one side of a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @olive oil{1%teaspoon},
@salt{}, and @pepper{} (for 4 servings, spread out across entire sheet).

Roast on top rack for ~{5%minutes} (you'll add more to the sheet then).

Meanwhile, in a #medium bowl{}, soak @panko breadcrumbs{¼%cup} with @water{1%tbsp}
(2 TBSP for 4 servings) and @beef stock concentrate{1} until liquid has absorbed.
Add @ground beef{10%ounce}, @salt{½%tsp} (1 tsp for 4), and pepper; mix to combine.

Form beef mixture into two ½-inch-thick rounds (four rounds for 4). Reserve
half the @cheddar cheese{½%cup} for topping; divide remaining cheddar between
the centers of each round. Gently fold meat around cheese, shaping and sealing
to create 1-inch-thick loaves.

Once potatoes have roasted ~{5%minutes}, remove sheet from #oven{}. Add meatloaves
to opposite side of sheet. (For 4 servings, leave potatoes roasting; add meatloaves
to a second sheet and roast on middle rack.)

Roast on top rack until potatoes are browned and tender and meatloaves are
cooked through, ~{17-20%minutes} more.

In the last ~{2%minutes} of roasting, top meatloaves with reserved cheddar.
Return to oven until cheese melts.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%teaspoon} in a large, #heavy-bottomed pan{}
over medium-high heat. Add carrots and a pinch of salt and pepper; cook,
stirring occasionally, until browned and softened, ~{5-7%minutes}.

> If carrots begin to brown too quickly, add a few splashes of water.

Turn off heat; transfer carrots to a #plate{}. Wipe out pan.

> Swap in asparagus for carrots. Cook 3-5 minutes.

In a #small bowl{}, toss shallot with @flour{1%tablespoon} and a pinch of salt
and pepper.

In pan used for carrots, heat a 1/3-inch layer of @oil{} over medium heat.
Once oil is hot enough that a pinch of flour sizzles immediately when added to
the pan, add coated shallot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until golden brown,
~{3-5%minutes}.

Using a #slotted spoon{}, transfer shallot to a #paper-towel-lined plate{}.

Meanwhile, in a separate small bowl, combine @ketchup{1} and @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon}.
Stir in water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.
Season with salt and pepper.

Slice meatloaves crosswise if desired.

Divide meatloaves, potato wedges, and carrots between plates. Drizzle meatloaves
with some of the special sauce. Serve remaining sauce on the side with potatoes
for dipping. Garnish meatloaves with crispy shallot and serve.

> Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.